Chatham and Badre

Page 14

Figure 2. Basal ganglia (BG) contributions to working memory input control. (a) A meta-analysis of over 8000 studies, carried out with Neurosynth’s python package [53], reveals that studies with abstracts including the term ‘updating’ are significantly more likely to report a BOLD response in the bilateral BG (Z = 2.58–7.03, FDR to p < .05; among other regions, not shown). (b) Binding of the competitive dopamine agonist raclopride within the BG is decreased during an updating task (letter memory), relative to a control task (Stroop). (c) Individual differences in D2 binding affinity within the bilateral BG predict individual differences in the rapid updating of working memory (as assessed by the attentional blink), uniquely throughout the brain (even at a liberal threshold of p < .01). (b,c) adapted from [27,29•] respectively.

